{"title_page": "Vulnerability management", "text_new": "{{Refimprove |date=June 2013}}\n\n'''Vulnerability management''' is the \"cyclical practice of identifying, classifying, prioritizing, remediating, and mitigating\" [[Software vulnerability| software vulnerabilities]].<ref>Foreman, P: ''Vulnerability Management'', page 1. Taylor & Francis Group, 2010. {{ISBN|978-1-4398-0150-5}}</ref> Vulnerability management is integral to [[computer security]] and [[network security]], and must not be confused with [[Vulnerability assessment]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hitachi-systems-security.com/blog/difference-vulnerability-assessments-vulnerability-management/|title=Vulnerability Assessments vs. Vulnerability Management|date=2018-02-19|work=Hitachi Systems Security {{!}} Managed Security Services Provider|access-date=2018-08-04|language=en-US}}</ref>.{{promotional source|date=December 2018}}\n\nVulnerabilities can be discovered with a [[vulnerability scanner]], which analyzes a computer system in search of known vulnerabilities,<ref name=\"Codenomicon\">Anna-Maija Juuso and Ari Takanen ''Unknown Vulnerability Management'', Codenomicon whitepaper, October 2010 [http://www.codenomicon.com/solutions/unknown-vulnerability-management/].</ref> such as [[open port]]s, insecure software configurations, and susceptibility to [[malware]] infections. While traditional vulnerability management focuses mostly on [[Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures|CVEs (common vulnerabilities and exposures)]], modern vulnerability management takes into account security issues like weak passwords, password reuse, users clicking on phishing emails, and unencrypted communications<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.balbix.com/resources/ebook-most-common-cybersecurity-attack-vectors-and-breach-methods/|title=Most Common Attack Vectors and Breach Methods|date=2020-01-13|website=Balbix|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>. They may also be identified by consulting public sources, such as NVD, or subscribing to a commercial vulnerability alerting service such as Symantec's DeepSight Vulnerability Datafeed<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.symantec.com/en/hk/services/cyber-security-services/deepsight-intelligence/technical-intelligence |title=DeepSight Technical Intelligence {{!}} Symantec |website=www.symantec.com|access-date=2018-12-05}}</ref>{{promotional source|date=December 2018}}  or Accenture's Vulnerability Intelligence Service<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accenture.com/t20170721T105740Z__w__/us-en/_acnmedia/PDF-57/Accenture-IDefense-Vulnerability-Intelligence.pdf |website=www.accenture.com| access-date=2018-12-05}}</ref>.{{promotional source|date=December 2018}}  Unknown vulnerabilities, such as a [[Zero-day (computing)|zero-day]],<ref name=\"Codenomicon\" /> may be found with [[fuzz testing]], which can identify certain kinds of vulnerabilities, such as a [[buffer overflow]] with relevant [[test case]]s. Such analysis can be facilitated by [[test automation]]. In addition, [[antivirus software]] capable of [[Heuristic (computer science)|heuristic]] analysis may discover undocumented malware if it finds software behaving suspiciously (such as attempting to overwrite a [[system file]]).\n\nCorrecting vulnerabilities may variously involve the [[Installation (computer programs)|installation]] of a [[Patch (computing)|patch]], a change in network security policy, reconfiguration of software, or educating [[User (computing)|users]] about [[Social engineering (security)|social engineering]].\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Application security]]\n*[[Full disclosure (computer security)|Full disclosure]]\n*[[Long-term support]]\n*[[IT risk]]\n*[[Risk management]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.sans.org/reading-room/whitepapers/threats/implementing-vulnerability-management-process-34180 \"Implementing a Vulnerability Management Process\"]. ''SANS Institute.'' \n[[Category:Computer network security]]\n[[Category:Computer security procedures]]\n[[Category:Security compliance]]\n[[Category:Computer security exploits|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove |date=June 2013}}\n\n'''Vulnerability management''' is the \"cyclical practice of identifying, classifying, prioritizing, remediating, and mitigating\" [[Software vulnerability| software vulnerabilities]].<ref>Foreman, P: ''Vulnerability Management'', page 1. Taylor & Francis Group, 2010. {{ISBN|978-1-4398-0150-5}}</ref> Vulnerability management is integral to [[computer security]] and [[network security]], and must not be confused with [[Vulnerability assessment]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hitachi-systems-security.com/blog/difference-vulnerability-assessments-vulnerability-management/|title=Vulnerability Assessments vs. Vulnerability Management|date=2018-02-19|work=Hitachi Systems Security {{!}} Managed Security Services Provider|access-date=2018-08-04|language=en-US}}</ref>.{{promotional source|date=December 2018}}\n\nVulnerabilities can be discovered with a [[vulnerability scanner]], which analyzes a computer system in search of known vulnerabilities,<ref name=\"Codenomicon\">Anna-Maija Juuso and Ari Takanen ''Unknown Vulnerability Management'', Codenomicon whitepaper, October 2010 [http://www.codenomicon.com/solutions/unknown-vulnerability-management/].</ref> such as [[open port]]s, insecure software configurations, and susceptibility to [[malware]] infections. They may also be identified by consulting public sources, such as NVD, or subscribing to a commercial vulnerability alerting service such as Symantec's DeepSight Vulnerability Datafeed<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.symantec.com/en/hk/services/cyber-security-services/deepsight-intelligence/technical-intelligence |title=DeepSight Technical Intelligence {{!}} Symantec |website=www.symantec.com|access-date=2018-12-05}}</ref>{{promotional source|date=December 2018}}  or Accenture's Vulnerability Intelligence Service<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accenture.com/t20170721T105740Z__w__/us-en/_acnmedia/PDF-57/Accenture-IDefense-Vulnerability-Intelligence.pdf |website=www.accenture.com| access-date=2018-12-05}}</ref>.{{promotional source|date=December 2018}}  Unknown vulnerabilities, such as a [[Zero-day (computing)|zero-day]],<ref name=\"Codenomicon\" /> may be found with [[fuzz testing]], which can identify certain kinds of vulnerabilities, such as a [[buffer overflow]] with relevant [[test case]]s. Such analysis can be facilitated by [[test automation]]. In addition, [[antivirus software]] capable of [[Heuristic (computer science)|heuristic]] analysis may discover undocumented malware if it finds software behaving suspiciously (such as attempting to overwrite a [[system file]]).\n\nCorrecting vulnerabilities may variously involve the [[Installation (computer programs)|installation]] of a [[Patch (computing)|patch]], a change in network security policy, reconfiguration of software, or educating [[User (computing)|users]] about [[Social engineering (security)|social engineering]].\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Application security]]\n*[[Full disclosure (computer security)|Full disclosure]]\n*[[Long-term support]]\n*[[IT risk]]\n*[[Risk management]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.sans.org/reading-room/whitepapers/threats/implementing-vulnerability-management-process-34180 \"Implementing a Vulnerability Management Process\"]. ''SANS Institute.'' \n[[Category:Computer network security]]\n[[Category:Computer security procedures]]\n[[Category:Security compliance]]\n[[Category:Computer security exploits|*]]\n", "name_user": "NDBrad", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added in sentence on CVEs and types of vulnerabilities", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vulnerability_management"}
